<head>
<title>Your Guide to ARD Meetings in Midway ISD</title>
<link href="/style.css" rel="stylesheet"/>
</head>
<body>
<h2>What Is an ARD Meeting?</h2>
<p>Welcome to the world of ARD meetings! As a parent of a child with special needs in Midway ISD, understanding the ARD process is essential for ensuring your child receives the best possible education. ARD stands for Admission, Review, and Dismissal. This meeting is the cornerstone of special education services, where crucial decisions about your child's educational journey are made. The ARD committee, which includes you as a vital member, comes together to develop, review, and revise your child's Individualized Education Program, often referred to as an IEP. This IEP is a roadmap outlining the specific supports and services your child needs to succeed in school.</p>
<p>The purpose of the ARD meeting is multifaceted. First, it's about determining if your child is eligible for special education services. If eligible, the committee crafts an individualized education program designed to address your child's unique needs. The IEP includes present levels of academic achievement and functional performance, measurable annual goals, specific special education and related services, and appropriate accommodations and modifications. The ARD committee also decides on the least restrictive environment (LRE) where your child will receive their education, aiming for inclusion in general education settings to the greatest extent possible, with supports.</p>
<p>Who attends the ARD meeting? The ARD committee is composed of several key individuals. You, as the parent, are a central member of the team and your input is invaluable. A representative of the school district who is qualified to provide or supervise the provision of specially designed instruction is also required. This person is usually an administrator or special education director. Your child's general education teacher (if applicable) and special education teacher also participate, providing insights into your child's performance in the classroom. Other individuals with knowledge or special expertise regarding your child may also be included, such as related service providers (speech therapists, occupational therapists, counselors), educational diagnosticians, or even individuals you invite to support you. It is also important to note that your child may attend the ARD meeting, when appropriate. When your child is 16 years of age or older, the ARD meeting must also address transition services planning to prepare your child for life after high school.</p>
<p>The ARD meeting is not just a suggestion; it's a legal requirement. The Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) and Texas Education Code 29 mandate that schools provide a free and appropriate public education (FAPE) to children with disabilities. The ARD process is the mechanism by which this legal obligation is fulfilled.</p>
<h2>Your 5-Day Notice Right</h2>
<p>Before any ARD meeting takes place, Midway ISD is required to provide you with written notice at least five calendar days in advance. This 5-day notice is your opportunity to prepare for the meeting and gather any information you feel is relevant to your child's education. This notice is not just a formality; it's your legal right under IDEA and Texas Education Code.</p>
<p>What information must be included in the 5-day notice? The notice must specify the purpose of the meeting, such as an initial evaluation, annual review, or a change in placement. It must also list the proposed agenda items that will be discussed during the meeting. Perhaps most importantly, the notice must identify who will be attending the ARD meeting, including their roles and titles. This allows you to know who will be present and their potential perspectives.</p>
<p>You have the right to waive the 5-day notice requirement if you choose to meet sooner. Perhaps you have a scheduling conflict later in the week, or you simply want to address the matter quickly. In these cases, you can provide written consent to waive the 5-day notice. However, you should only do this if you feel fully prepared and comfortable proceeding with the meeting.</p>
<h2>What to Bring to Your ARD</h2>
<p>Preparation is key to a successful ARD meeting. Bringing the right information and resources can empower you to actively participate and advocate for your child's needs. Here's a detailed list of items you should consider bringing to your ARD meeting:</p>
<p>First, gather any prior evaluations, assessments, or reports related to your child's educational or developmental history. This includes evaluations from private psychologists, therapists, or medical professionals. These documents provide valuable insights into your child's strengths, weaknesses, and areas where they may need additional support. Ensure these reports are organized and easily accessible during the meeting.</p>
<p>Bring any letters or reports from your child's doctors, particularly if they relate to your child's disability or medical needs. These letters can provide medical context for educational decisions and help the ARD committee understand the potential impact of medical conditions on your child's learning. For example, a letter from a neurologist explaining the impact of ADHD on your child's attention span can inform decisions about classroom accommodations.</p>
<p>Gather any relevant school records, such as report cards, progress reports, and attendance records. These documents provide a snapshot of your child's academic performance and behavior in the classroom. Review these records carefully before the meeting so you can identify any trends or patterns that may need to be addressed.</p>
<p>Prepare a written list of your specific concerns and questions. Having your thoughts organized on paper will help you stay focused during the meeting and ensure that all of your concerns are addressed. This list might include concerns about your child's academic progress, social skills, behavior, or any other issues that you feel are impacting their education.</p>
<p>Don't go it alone! Bring a trusted advocate or support person to the ARD meeting. This could be a friend, family member, or a professional advocate who is familiar with special education laws and procedures. Having a support person can provide emotional support, help you take notes, and ensure that your voice is heard.</p>
<p>In Texas, it is legal to audio record ARD meetings, provided you give notice to the other participants that you are doing so. A voice recorder can be a valuable tool for documenting the meeting and ensuring that you have an accurate record of the discussions and decisions made. This can be helpful for future reference or if any disagreements arise later on.</p>
<h2>The 10-Day Recess Rule</h2>
<p>The ARD committee process is collaborative. You have the right, as does any member of the ARD committee, to request a recess of the meeting for up to 10 school days. This "10-day recess rule" provides an opportunity to gather more information, consult with experts, or simply take time to process the information discussed during the meeting before making any final decisions. This is a powerful tool to ensure decisions are well informed and thoughtfully considered.</p>
<p>How do you invoke the 10-day recess rule? Simply state that you would like to invoke the recess rule and specify the reason for your request. For example, you might say, "I would like to invoke the 10-day recess rule because I want to consult with an advocate before finalizing the IEP." The ARD committee must grant your request for a recess of up to 10 school days. The meeting will then be reconvened at a mutually agreed upon date and time.</p>
<h2>Understanding the IEP Document</h2>
<p>The IEP document is the heart of the ARD process. It's a comprehensive plan that outlines your child's present levels of performance, annual goals, services, placement, and accommodations. Understanding the components of the IEP is crucial for ensuring that your child receives the appropriate supports and services.</p>
<p>Present levels of academic achievement and functional performance describe your child's current skills and abilities in various areas, such as reading, writing, math, social skills, and behavior. This section should provide a clear picture of your child's strengths and weaknesses. Annual goals are measurable objectives that your child is expected to achieve within a year. These goals should be specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound (SMART goals).</p>
<p>Services refer to the specific special education and related services that your child will receive. This might include specialized instruction, speech therapy, occupational therapy, counseling, or transportation. Placement refers to the educational setting where your child will receive their services. The goal is to place your child in the least restrictive environment (LRE), which means that they should be educated with their non-disabled peers to the greatest extent possible. Accommodations are changes to the way instruction or assessments are delivered to help your child access the curriculum. This might include extended time on tests, preferential seating, or the use of assistive technology.</p>
<p>Remember, you are not required to sign the IEP on the same day as the ARD meeting. Take your time to review the document carefully and ensure that you understand all of its components. You have the right to request changes or revisions to the IEP if you disagree with any aspect of it.</p>
<h2>When You Disagree With the Team</h2>
<p>It's important to remember that you are an equal member of the ARD committee, and your voice matters. If you disagree with the team's decisions, you have several rights and options available to you. You have the right to refuse consent for initial placement in special education. This means that the school cannot place your child in special education services without your permission.</p>
<p>You are not obligated to sign the IEP if you disagree with it. If you disagree with any aspect of the IEP, you can refuse to sign it. By not signing, you are not consenting to the plan as written. You also have the right to request an Independent Educational Evaluation (IEE) at the district's expense if you disagree with the school's evaluation of your child. An IEE is an evaluation conducted by a qualified professional who is not employed by the school district. This evaluation can provide an independent perspective on your child's needs.</p>
<p>Even if you choose to sign the IEP, you can write "parent disagrees" on the document next to your signature. This indicates that you do not fully agree with the IEP and preserves your right to pursue other options if necessary.</p>
<h2>Escalation Options</h2>
<p>If you are unable to resolve your disagreements with the ARD committee, there are several formal escalation options available to you. These options are governed by IDEA 2004 and 19 TAC Chapter 89, both of which are outlined in the Legal Framework. Here are the four options, presented in order:</p>
<p>First, you can file a complaint with the Texas Education Agency (TEA). This is a free process, and TEA is required to resolve the complaint within 60 days. The complaint must allege a violation of IDEA or state special education law. This option is often used for procedural violations.</p>
<p>Second, you can request mediation through TEA. Mediation is a voluntary process in which a neutral third party helps you and the school district reach a mutually agreeable resolution. This is also a free service provided by TEA. Mediation can be a valuable tool for resolving disputes in a collaborative and constructive manner.</p>
<p>Third, you can request a Due Process Hearing. This is a more formal legal process in which an impartial hearing officer hears evidence and makes a decision about your child's special education needs. You have the right to be represented by an attorney at a Due Process Hearing. Due Process Hearings can be complex and time-consuming, so it's important to carefully consider whether this is the right option for you.</p>
<p>Finally, you can file a complaint with the Federal Office for Civil Rights (OCR). This option is available if you believe that the school district has discriminated against your child based on their disability. OCR investigations can be broad in scope and may address systemic issues within the school district.</p>























